   "source": [
    "## Hold-up Tank Model\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook will show the basics of using fmdtools to simulate hazards in a system with human-component interactions, including:\n",
    "\n",
    "- human-induced failure modes\n",
    "- human responses to component failure modes\n",
    "- joint human-component failure modes\n",
    "\n",
    "The system to model is in `tank_model.py`.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Copyright © 2024, United States Government, as represented by the Administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. All rights reserved.\n",
    "\n",
    "The “\"Fault Model Design tools - fmdtools version 2\"” software is licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\"); you may not use this file except in compliance with the License. You may obtain a copy of the License at http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0. \n",
    "\n",
    "Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS, WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied. See the License for the specific language governing permissions and limitations under the License.\n",
    "```"

    "from fmdtools.define.architecture.function import FunctionArchitectureGraph"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Verifying the nominal state:\n",
    "\n",
    "In the nominal state, no change in system state should occur and the tank level should remain at 10. For this, `track = 'all'` is included to record all states of the model. If `track = 'all'` is ommitted, only values defined in `mdl.default_track` would be included (see `tank_model.py`)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mdl = Tank(track='all')\n",
    "result, mdlhist = propagate.nominal(mdl, desired_result={'graph': FunctionArchitectureGraph})"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### What happens under component faults?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we model a leak of the tank. To compensate for this leak, the operator opens the first valve to a higher setting, maintaining the level of the tank. This is done with `propagate.one_fault`, which tells the model that a fault has occured and when it did occure. Note that this fault was part of the history earlier as `fxns.store_water.m.faults.leak`. \n",
    "\n",
    "Here, the store_water level drops until the indicator turns on and allows for the system to compensate to keep the tank from fully emptying. Blue represents nominal state and red is the fault scenario."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-03-11T00:16:03.295775Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-03-11T00:16:03.295775Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-03-11T00:16:03.794096Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-03-11T00:16:03.794096Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [

     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x400 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "resgraph, mdlhist = propagate.one_fault(mdl,'store_water','leak', time=3,track='all',desired_result=['graph','endclass','endfaults'])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = mdlhist.plot_line('flows.valve1_sig.s.action', 'flows.tank_sig.s.indicator',\n",
    "                            'fxns.store_water.s.level', 'fxns.store_water.s.net_flow',\n",
    "                            title=\"Tank response to leak at t=3\", time_slice=3, legend_loc=False, title_padding=0.1)\n"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can also view the model again with highlighed areas to show the faults visually. The `draw_from` function requires both the time step you're call (here, it's at `10` since that is after the fault occured). For more uses of this function, including animations, see `Pump_Example_Notebook.ipynb` in the pump example folder."
   ]

   "source": [
    "Note how, compared to the previos history table, this one does not include all values rather only the component that was affected (IE the store water function. We can further us `History.get_degraded_hist` compares the results over time so we can see what functions and flows were degraded over time. We can then use the summary to view a list of the functions and flows that were impacted over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can the the view it as a table again, but compared to the previous it only shows if the fault occurs."

    "### Evaluating Joint Component-Human fault modes \n",
    "\n",
    "To understand where the risks of failure are, we need to find the scenarios, that, with the modelled human controls, still lead to failures. To assess this, we develop a fault sampling strategy using `FaultDomain` and `FaultSample`."
   ]
